2/23/99

    Before, in SPLICE mode, we process the off (master) picture on at a time.
    With missing PTS, we now use a loop to exhause all appropriate master
    channel pictures.  As a result, it seems that we no longer need to
    clean off off channel picture before switching to SPLICE state!
    (Delete second while loop in processOnChanPreroll().

    Why do I need onChanReady and offChanReady,
        for preroll mode?
        for splice mode?

    In PREROLL state, onChanReady indicates whether onChanPts/Dts are valid.
    They are necessary since off channel processing is locked with on channel
    DTS.  However, I don't think offChanReady is necessary in PREROLL state.

    DECIDED TO REMOVE DTS LOCKING.
    Rewrote switcher.c state machine.

    The current way of determining exit time is not reliable since
    prevFrmDI may not associate with the exit picture.
    A better way is to use next picture in on channle, and in case it is
    not available, exit doSplice and wait for the next call of doSplice.
    The only drawback of this new approach is that if there is no more
    picture from the on channel after the exit picture.
    (exit picture is the first coded picture to drop in on channel)

    A even better way is to keep track of the last P frame which is
    before the splice point.  Should use this method later.


